headline: Dollar General lifts annual targets on steady demand for affordable essentials
summary: (Reuters) -Dollar General raised its annual targets on Thursday, banking on resilient demand from cost-conscious consumers across income brackets in the United States, looking to stretch their budgets in the face of tariff and inflation concerns.  Dollar General raised its annual earnings per share target to between $5.80 and $6.30, from $5.20 to $5.80 per share, as it also benefits from cost savings through its two store-remodeling projects to fix product placements and merchandising.  U.S. President Donald Trump's import tariffs had already resulted in some price increases, Dollar General CEO Todd Vasos said in a post-earnings call.

headline: ?Consumer Pain Is Dollar Stores' Gain
summary: Middle and high-income consumers have been flocking to dollar stores this year, helping catapult those retailers’ year-to-date stock gains above Nvidia’s.  Dollar Tree and Dollar General, the latter of which reports earnings today, have each gained close to 50% this year, making them the top two brick-and-mortar retail stocks in the S&P 500.  Dollar General said in its June earnings call that it saw the highest percentage of trade-down customers in the past four years.
